Why America must not re-elect President Bush
I have never been politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was damned by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran for office in 2000 with a platform promising an "humility" foreign policy.
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot box, America has a chance to regain the world's respect and support.
The terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
However, it has also led to the dismissal of the critical process essential for democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of impending problems.
Bush silenced criticism by declaring it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
Actually, Bush had directly handed Osama bin Laden a victory.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
It was an unintended gift from Bush to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America occurred all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
Clearly more people are willing to risk their lives today to kill Americans than on September 11.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, bring forth innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Similarly, the torture of prisoners at Abu Ghraib was not the work of a few "rotten apples".
She was part of a system for dealing with detainees established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public opinion condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush convinced people that America's security was in good hands with him by addressing the fears aroused by the attacks on September 11.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will almost believe anything if you repeat it often enough.
There must be something wrong with America if we fall for it.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with September 11, despite the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly establishing that such a connection did not exist.
One would scream: "Wake up, America."
Don't you realize that we're being led by the nose?
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from start to finish - if it ends.
It was a war of its own choosing, not out of necessity.
More importantly, America was dragged into war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the link to Al Qaeda could not be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to liberate Iraq.
But democracy cannot be imposed on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we passively watched as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If it had been truly about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a much larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We had to protect not only the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they employed methods - such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population, thereby fostering resentment and anger.
The missteps and U-turns of the Bush administration are countless.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the United States sought to eliminate the Baathists, then America tried to win their support.
When the uprisings could no longer be managed, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as your leader was a CIA protégé with the reputation of a "strong man" - far from a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to paint a rosy picture, the situation in Iraq is grim.
A large part of the western province was left to the insurgents. The prospects for the conduct of free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted immense damage on America, weakening its military strength and undermining the morale of its troops.
Before the war, America projected an image of overwhelming strength.
Not anymore.
Afghanistan slips out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration in many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war amount to nearly 200 billion dollars so far and will continue to rise, as the withdrawal from Iraq will prove to be much more difficult than the invasion was.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But this will not come easily to him either, for America is mired in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats pleaded with Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the commander-in-chief endangered the US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should pause and ask themselves: Whom do we owe this mess to?
A moment of reflection might raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy behavior qualify him to remain America's commander-in-chief?
